<br>
Wizards are one of the most fun classes to play in the game. Rombus related a situation where he was playing a well equipped monk and found his group was losing kills to the wizard group. They <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> tried</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to get a kill but couldn't. If you think about it, there's not a lot that a melee class can do to increase their damage output. Once their group and equipment is set, their damage output is pretty much determined by the dice gods, and there's not a lot they can do to change it increase their output. Wizards, on the other hand, have complete control over this. Just having control over when and how hard to nuke means you are constantly making decisions in combat. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ualedar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aledar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 186<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/6/02 3:34 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: It's depressing</span><hr size=1> Etnu, dunno if I was clear enough on it before, maybe not, but I'm definitely looking more at a high-end point of view.  Face it, I do most of my grouping within Recon, and report what I see.  Your results will vary with level 52 warriors using Wurmslayers and Cane of the Tranquils, of course, plus whatever falls in between.  Point is, for the most part, all wizards are pretty much equal in damage output.  There's some variation, but not a whole lot, relatively.  Melees are very gear dependant.  We'll outdamage those with &quot;lesser&quot; gear, but those with the best to chose from will outdamage us over time.  But in exp groups with those in my guild, there's no way in hell I can outdamage a warrior, rogue, monk or ranger... SKs and Paladins are rather out of reach, hell, Bards can probably outdamage me overall.<br>
<br>
Also, moving through a zone to a raid target is a bit different from your average exp group.  Your PoG yard trash is inherently different from your most popular pickup group spots - mushrooms in FG, spiders in Velks, etc.  In other words, easy mobs that you can literally pull nonstop.  In such situations (which most exp groups strive to emulate), there will be pretty much no &quot;recharging&quot; time for us.  Moving through some hard yard trash is different.<br>
<br>
Take NToV a couple of weeks ago.  I was in the wiz-heavy group.  16 named mobs, 14 we got exp from.  Problem is, that was ALL we got, with a couple exceptions - two baby drakes (where our guild policy is &quot;hit F8 and keel at will&quot;), and two Vulak guards while half the guild was dispelling and working out loot.  So during the entire clearing, I got just over a blue of alt exp.  Many offtanks got 2-3 yellow.  And it's not like we weren't trying, we just couldn't regen mana fast enough to keep up with the pulls, so our damage suffered as a result.  Same result for Ring of Fire; we don't really get any exp on waves 3-5 except the boss mobs, which we always get.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, we were messing around with the Arch Lich the other day.  Eight guards right outside him, all yellow cons, we got most of the exp.  The fights were long enough, though not too long, and spaced out enough for us to regain mana.  Hence, exp for us.  Similar things happen with the elder thought horrors around Overfiend.  It's *all* about how fast stuff is being pulled, and how fast they die.<br>
<br>
Like I said, we're situational.  I provided a few examples above for our strengths and weaknesses.  The problem for your average level 53 wizard looking for a pickup group is that the &quot;perfect group&quot; that most people strive to obtain are our weakness, and people notice before long.  Is the difference as bad in the low 50's for similar equipped characters?  Not that much.  But the damage difference can get out of hand with a few melee gear improvements, and as a result, people seem almost afraid to group wizards because they might be less efficient.  Sometimes, people just take the whole max/min thing way too far... but sometimes, the gap really is too big to justify if other classes are available.  It's not *all* because of our decreased efficiency in situations, but it does play a part, be it directly or indirectly.<br>
<br>
It's almost funny, in a way... one of the &quot;required&quot; classes for most Kunark groups, the cleric, is getting left behind as well, at least in the high-end game.  Monks with top of the line gear can just totally shread through most level 45 mobs for exp... one in my guild took out 3 blues at once the other night, only lost 2 bubbles of life in the process.  A monk/shaman duo is just sick now.  And as your average armor keeps getting better and better (your average player seems to have a good deal of Thurgadin armor or equivalent these days), shamans are taking over cleric spots.  Even chanters are getting to be dead weight compared to bards in a lot of spots.  Players are getting to be more &quot;uber&quot; than Verant ever imagined they would, IMHO, and Verant is forced to make changes as they go along.<br>
<br>
In the end, I do enjoy playing my wizard now.  Casters are getting some good stuff in Luclin (though the most helpful, like Flowing Thought, is still pretty much exclusive to the larger guilds).  But there's definitely some parts that need some tinkering to iron things out, and I think that exp situations need a closer look. <p><a href="http://www.reconstructed.nu/profile.php?pid=119">Baron Aledar Boomcaster</a><br>Sorcerer of <a href="http://www.reconstructed.nu/">Reconstructed</a>, E'ci<br><img src="http://www.seas.upenn.edu/~bwa/kerasig.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uwhizbangdustyboots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Whizbang Dustyboots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<BR>Gnomish Advocate</span><br>  Posts: 4818<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/6/02 3:40 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: It's depressing</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> your average player seems to have a good deal of Thurgadin armor or equivalent these days<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
